@findex dslide-push-step
@cindex pushing steps
You can use @code{dslide-push-step} for inserting arbitrary callbacks that can function as steps.  Like everything else in dslide@comma{} returning non-nil means progress was made and the step should be consumed.  By adding these inside babel blocks@comma{} you can add extra steps that depend on the next direction.

The callback function should accept a DIRECTION argument.  DIRECTION is forward@comma{} backward@comma{} or nil.  nil just means the presentation is ending or displaying the contents@comma{} so you should clean up instead of attempting to do work.
@example
#+begin_src elisp
  (message "Just doing block things")

  ;; Let's also push a step!
  (dslide-push-step
   (lambda (direction)
     ;; Decide what to do
     (pcase direction
       ;; `message' returns non-nil and will function as a padding step
       (forward (message "Injecting an extra step"))
       ;; `prog1' nil returns the nil@comma{} so this will not add a step
       (backward (prog1 nil (message "No step for you!")))
       ;; The _ catch-all will handle non-directional calls@comma{} such as quitting
       (_ (prog1 nil (message "Cleaning üí© up!"))))))
#+end_src

@end example
